statement.p:
Let 

                    \eta = \sum_{1 \leq i_1 \lt \cdots \lt i_m \leq n} f_{i_1, \ldots ,i_m } \, \tder{}{x_{i_1}} \wedge \cdots \wedge \tder{}{x_{i_m}}

                    be a differential m-form in \mathbb{R}^n. The exterior derivative of \eta is the (m + 1)-form 

                    \tder{}{\eta} = \sum_{1 \leq i_1 \lt \cdots \lt i_m \leq n} \tder{}{f_{i_1, \ldots ,i_m }} \wedge  \tder{}{x_{i_1}} \wedge \cdots \wedge \tder{}{x_{i_m}}

For a differentiable vector field \mb{F}
                    defined on an open subset U of \mathbb{R}^3 endowed with the dot product and standard orientation,

                    \text{curl} (\mb{F} ) = \left[ \star \left( \tder{}{\mb{F}^\vee} \right) \right]^\vee.

Let U be an open subset of 3-dimensional Euclidean space.
                    Using only the square zero property, , , and  show that for any twice differentiable function f and vector field \mb{F} defined on U we have

                        \text{curl} \left( \nabla f \right) = \mb{0}
                        \hspace{.2in} \text{and} \hspace{.2in}
                        \text{div} \left( \text{curl} (\mb{F} ) \right) = 0.
